{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"33d163ac-28e2-4465-a6c9-51a6964fe7b5","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool inside the container\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **speedscope** format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available, use **`dotnet-dump`** for a quick snapshot, or **`perf`** for native + managed stacks.\n- Copy the trace out with `kubectl cp <pod>:<path> ./trace.nettrace`.\n- For production, consider `--buffersize 512` if you're dropping events.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"303ed35b-4439-4b44-bfb4-56982276605a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I'll provide concise, practical guidance.","outputTokens":307,"requestId":"D81A:36DBF5:2107FB7:24A0B0E:6A03D48A"},"id":"bfe31e24-0a89-47fd-b878-860d131917e3","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:32:02.859Z","parentId":"a6f428e9-f5fc-4f29-a735-c5c7fa2f1b48"}
